## 🔌 **How Relay Switching Works — Complete Technical Breakdown**

Your system uses **active-LOW relay logic** with a **priority-ordered state machine**. Let me break down exactly what happens:

---

### **1. Hardware Side: The Relay Module**

Your **4-channel opto-isolated relay module** works like this:

```
┌─────────────────────┐
│  ESP32 GPIO (3.3V)  │  HIGH (3.3V)  → Relay OFF → Load is ON
│                     │  LOW (0V)     → Relay ON  → Load is OFF
│  GPIO26 (Zone 1)    │
│  GPIO27 (Zone 2)    │
│  GPIO14 (Zone 3)    │
│  GPIO12 (Zone 4)    │
└─────────────────────┘
         ↓
   [Optocoupler]  ← Provides galvanic isolation
    (LED flashes)     (protects ESP32 from back-EMF spikes)
         ↓
   [Relay coil]   ← Electromagnet pulls metal contacts
         ↓
   [AC Load]      ← 220V AC equipment (AC unit, water heater, etc.)
```

**Why active-LOW?**
- **Safe default on boot**: If your firmware crashes, all relays default to OFF (they lose power), which is the safe state
- **Standard practice**: 99% of relay modules use this logic

---

### **2. Firmware Side: The Non-Blocking State Machine**

Your ESP32 firmware runs a **5-task non-blocking loop**. Every **2 seconds**, it does this:

```
Read PZEM Sensor
     ↓
Classify Load (is it > 2000W?)
     ↓
Update Baseline (rolling average for anomaly detection)
     ↓
RUN RELAY STATE MACHINE (for each zone)
     ↓
Push to Firebase
```

The **relay state machine** for each zone has **4 states**:

#### **State 1: MONITORING** (normal operation)
```
Current Power < 2000W
├─ GPIO = HIGH (relay OFF, load is ON/energised)
├─ Check every 2 seconds
└─ If power exceeds threshold → go to CONFIRMING
```

**Why we check every 2 seconds?**
- PZEM reads are every 2 seconds (hardware limitation)
- No point checking faster than sensor data arrives
- 2 seconds is fast enough for energy management decisions

---

#### **State 2: CONFIRMING** (verification)
```
Power > 2000W confirmed
├─ Start 10-second countdown
├─ At t+2s, t+4s, t+6s, t+8s: RE-CHECK power level
├─ If power drops below 2000W anytime → reset timer, go back to MONITORING
│  (this prevents false trips from momentary spikes like motor inrush)
└─ If timer reaches 10 seconds → trip the relay
```

**Why 10 seconds?**
- Your firmware code: `#define CONFIRM_MS 10000`
- Motor inrush currents last ~1-2 seconds → 10s is safe
- Quick enough to prevent energy waste
- Long enough to avoid nuisance trips

**Here's the actual firmware code that does this:**

```cpp
if (live.w > THRESH_W) {
  // Start confirmation timer on FIRST threshold breach
  if (zones[z].overSince == 0) 
    zones[z].overSince = now;

  // Wait for confirmation hold period
  if (now - zones[z].overSince < CONFIRM_MS) {
    Serial.printf("Zone %d: %.0fW > 2000W — hold %lus/%lus\n",
      z + 1, live.w, 
      (now - zones[z].overSince) / 1000,  // elapsed seconds
      CONFIRM_MS / 1000);                  // total seconds needed
    continue;
  }
  // If we get here, 10 seconds have ACTUALLY passed
  // Now we trip the relay
}
```

---

#### **State 3: TRIPPED** (load shedding)
```
Timer expired at exactly 10 seconds
├─ Execute: digitalWrite(GPIO_PIN, LOW)  
│  (This energises the relay coil, opening the AC load contacts)
├─ Load loses live wire → AC unit stops drawing power
├─ Start 30-second cooldown counter
└─ Log event to Firebase
```

**What happens at the relay:**
```
GPIO LOW (0V) → Optocoupler LED lights
             → Phototransistor sees light
             → Relay coil energises
             → Electromagnet pulls metal switch arm
             → Load contacts open (NC → open)
             → AC unit powered off
```

**Logging to Firebase:**
```cpp
fbPost("/events", 
  "{\"zone\":1,\"event\":\"TRIP\",\"w\":2341.2,\"ts\":1704067500000}");
```
This record appears in your dashboard event log.

---

#### **State 4: COOLDOWN** (relay protection)
```
Post-trip cooldown active
├─ Duration: 30 seconds (#define COOL_MS 30000)
├─ Ignore all new power readings
├─ NO relay re-arm attempts, even if power is still high
├─ After 30s → go back to MONITORING
└─ Reason: Protect relay contacts from mechanical chatter
           (opening/closing rapidly causes wear & EMI)
```

**Why 30 seconds?**
- Mechanical relays have contact "bounce" — they vibrate slightly when switching
- If we re-triggered after 1 second, we'd be: trip → reset → trip → reset → ...
- This wears out the relay and creates electrical noise
- 30 seconds is industry standard for load management systems
- By then, whatever caused the overload should be resolved

---

### **3. Priority Ordering** (The "Smart" Part)

When multiple zones could be tripped simultaneously, your firmware uses **priority ordering**:

```
Zone Priority Matrix:
┌──────────┬──────────┬──────────┐
│ Zone 1   │ Zone 2   │ Zone 4   │
│ AC unit  │ Heater   │ Lighting │
│ Priority │ Priority │ Priority │
│ 1 (trip  │ 2 (trip  │ 3 (trip  │
│  FIRST)  │  SECOND) │  THIRD)  │
└──────────┴──────────┴──────────┘

Zone 3 (Sockets): NEVER auto-trip (essential loads)
```

**The logic:**
```cpp
// Only trip if higher-priority zones already tripped
bool higherClear = true;
for (int j = 0; j < z; j++) {
  if (!zones[j].tripped && !zones[j].manual) 
    higherClear = false;  // Zone j is higher priority and NOT tripped yet
}

if (higherClear) {
  // All higher-priority zones either tripped OR manual
  // NOW we can trip this zone
  digitalWrite(relayPin, LOW);
  zones[z].tripped = true;
}
```

**Real-world example:**
```
Scenario: Total power = 2100W (all zones active)

t=0-10s:   MONITORING → Zone 1 confirms → TRIPPED
           Turns off AC unit (saves ~1500W immediately)
           
If power still > 2000W at t=30s (after cooldown):
t=30-40s:  Zone 2 confirms → TRIPPED  
           Turns off water heater (saves ~3000W)
           
If power STILL > 2000W:
t=60-70s:  Zone 4 confirms → TRIPPED
           Turns off lighting (saves ~200W)

Zone 3 (sockets with computers) STAYS ON always
→ User has light and power to laptop even in critical situation
```

---

### **4. Dashboard → ESP32 Command Flow**

When you toggle a relay from the web dashboard:

```
1. You click toggle in React dashboard
   └─ sendRelayCommand(1, false)  // Turn OFF Zone 1

2. Firebase receives: /relay_commands/z1 = false

3. ESP32 polls every 3 seconds:
   GET /relay_commands.json
   
4. Firmware parses JSON:
   if (desired != cmdCache[1]) {
     zones[0].manual = true;     // Flag as manual override
     zones[0].tripped = false;   // Clear auto-trip flag
     setRelay(1, false, "DASHBOARD_CMD");
     digitalWrite(GPIO26, LOW);  // Execute: load OFF
   }

5. Event logged to Firebase:
   /events → {zone: 1, event: "MANUAL_OFF", w: 891.4, ts: ...}

6. Dashboard event log updates in real-time
   showing the manual command was received
```

**Max command latency:** 3 seconds (polling interval)

---

### **5. The Complete Timeline Example**

```
Real-world scenario: AC unit in unoccupied office

t=0:00    | Power: 80W (lights, routers)
          | State: MONITORING
          |
t=5:00    | Someone leaves lights on + AC at full blast
          | Power: 2500W spike
          | State: MONITORING → CONFIRMING
          | Serial: "Zone 1: 2500W > 2000W — hold 2s/10s"
          |
t=6:00    | Power still 2400W (confirmed, not a transient)
          | Serial: "Zone 1: 2400W > 2000W — hold 4s/10s"
          |
t=8:00    | Power: 2350W
          | Serial: "Zone 1: 2350W > 2000W — hold 6s/10s"
          |
t=10:00   | 10-second hold expired → TRIP
          | GPIO26 → LOW (0V)
          | Relay energised, AC load contacts open
          | Serial: "[RELAY] Zone 1 (TRIP) → OFF | Reason: AUTO_TRIP"
          | Firebase /events: {zone: 1, event: "TRIP", w: 2350.0}
          | Power drops to 150W immediately
          |
t=10:00-40:00 | COOLDOWN period
          | Relay locked in OFF state
          | Even if power jumps back up, won't re-trip
          |
t=40:00   | Cooldown ends → back to MONITORING
          | If power < 2000W (it is), stays MONITORING
          | AC unit remains off (needs manual reset from dashboard)
          |
User receives SMS alert (if subscribed):
  "ALERT: Smart Energy Monitor
   Anomaly detected! Power: 2350W
   Z-score: 4.23
   Status: Critical threshold"
```

